<br> Compared to the first day it is found that the Pope "is much better, > we have seen improvements", although the picture remains "complex". Of course, the risk that worries the team is that " germs, today located in the respiratory tract and lungs", pass into the blood.
"In spite of all the therapies you do, if one of these germs passes into the blood it would have the sepsis > which for its age and its respiratory problem would be difficult to get out. This is the real risk," said Alfieri. At the moment, "there is no risk," he added, saying that the Pope "will be resigned and will return to Santa Marta>" because we work to cure the patient." "The chronic part will not heal, will remain, but the acute part will be resolved and the less acute part will be managed at Santa Marta."
"Timidally some medication was reduced but it is early" to evaluate the outcome. However, the Pope will remain admitted > "at least all next week", "until the time it is no longer necessary to administer hospital therapies. Pneumonia takes time to recover. He will continue to do therapy in Santa Marta".&nbsp;
